{
  "text": "T. gondii infection inhibited b-amyloid plaque formation in the cortex and hippocampus of Tg2576 mice Previous reports have indicated that inflammatory mediators stimulate amyloidogenesis in AD by inducing APP production and b-secretase expression [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the present study, we investigated whether suppression of neurodegeneration and the antiinflammatory cytokine increase observed in T. gondii-infected Tg2576 mice affect amyloidogenesis. The relationship between infection and b-amyloid deposition was examined by Congo red staining and immunohistochemistry in the brains of Tg2576 mice using b-amyloid specific 6E10 antibody, which specifically recognizes the 1-17 amino acid sequence of b-amyloid peptides ( Figure 3 ). Furthermore, whereas the brain tissues of wild type mice did not contain b-amyloid plaques by Congo red staining ( Figure 3A1 -2), Tg2576 mice typically generated considerable amounts of amyloid plaque ( Figure 3A3 , 3B), but T. gondii-infected Tg2576 mice exhibited obviously lower amounts of plaque ( Figure 3A4 , 3B). We also evaluated b-amyloid protein deposition by immunohistochemical (IHC) staining using 6E10 antibody ( Figure 3A5 , [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . It was found extracellular b-amyloid plaques in the cortex ( Figure 3A5 ) and hippocampal region ( Figure 3A7 ) of uninfected Tg2576 mice were remarkably greater than in T. gondiiinfected Tg2576 mice ( Figure 3A6, 3A8) , and that the number of plaques was significantly lower in T. gondii-infected Tg2576 mice in both hippocampus and cortex ( Figure 3B ).",
